description.plain:
Rhys Angelo Herbert (born 29 June 2000), better known by his stage name Digga D, is a drill rapper from Ladbroke Grove, West London.

Renowned for his unorthodox flow and his vivid lyrical imagery, he has had a steep rise to fame in the UK music scene over the past 12 months or so. He first made a mark on the scene with his freestyle on the “Next Up?” series that amassed 10 million views.

Digga D and CGM’s (previously known as 1011 and 916) music has gained notoriety in the mainstream media and amongst the police due to gang related content. This has led to a lot of their music being taken off sites such as YouTube and a court order banning 5 members of CGM, including Digga D from making drill music

It was predicted that if it was not taken down, CGM’s Next Up would have had 25 million views by now. The song has been credited as being a very important song in raising the profile of the UK drill scene and was an instant classic.

Other notable songs that have gained Digga D recognition are street anthems such as “Play For The Pagans”,  “No Hook” and “Kill Confirmed”, all of which manage to represent the reality of life on the streets of West London though the raw, unapologetic and unfiltered nature of his music.

Digga D released his debut commercial mixtape, Double Tap Diaries in June 2019. The tape was a critical and commercial success, charting at #11 on the UK Album Charts, being the very first Drill project to do so.

Digga’s reputation blew up following his release from prison in May 2020. A new court order was passed in which Digga’s music, lyrics and videos have to be run past police, who check them for forbidden references to violence or crime – it was well documented in his Documentary Defending Digga D, released on the 1st of December 2020, which showed Digga’s constant legal battle with the police.

Since his release, Digga’s hot streak include commercially successful tracks such as “Woi”, “Chingy (It’s Whatever)”, his Daily Duppy, as well as collaboration with Ladbroke Grove’s AJ Tracey on “Bringing It Back”. Digga’s 12-track sophomore mixtape Made In The Pyrex was released on the 26th of February 2021.

songs.title: No Diet

description.plain:
The highly anticipated release of “No Diet”, amplified by a London-wide publicity campaign that involved numerous members of the public, premiered on Mixtape Madness, yet again with producer Ghosty at the helm.



In what is a video that focuses on the highly taboo topic of crack cocaine production, Digga D explores avenues of UK drill music that he has, before “No Diet”, not pursued; namely the use of singing within parts of the second verse. His repeated use of beverage-related bars, with named drinks including coffee, Fosters and KA, accompanied by the light-hearted, playful tone within the structure of Digga D’s chorus and verses help to draw attention away from the violent themes that are ever present throughout the song.



When it comes to the visuals, led by @teeeezyc, we are exposed to a setting that takes place primarily in a modern suburban house; with a change up in scenery on a number of occasions showing Digga D and fellow CGM members on a golf course. As for the main topic at hand that is the crack cocaine production, we are – much like in K Trap’s music video for “Watching” – offered an alternative, visually, for the narcotic substance in the form of cans of Coca-Cola – once again relating back to the title of the song; “No Diet”.

description.plain:
Daily Duppy stands as the rebuilt bridge between Ladbroke Grove, West London artist Digga D and UK Music platform GRM Daily as they finally link up for Digga’s first appearance on their channel.

In November during an Instagram Q&A, Digga D gave the blunt answer when a fan asked why he hasn’t done a Daily Duppy yet:



It was rumoured that GRM Daily do not endorse Digga’s West London collective CGM/1011 but promote his rivals such as Loski and Fredo – who he brandishes as “lying ass niggas” – which he took offence at.

With his highly anticipated Daily Duppy coming out a month after the dispute, Digga rides two separate beats as he talks about battling his opps, his recent release from prison, influence in the UK Drill Scene whilst sparing no time for ingenious word-play and puns.

description.plain:
“Woi” is Ladbroke Grove, West London rapper Digga D’s return single after a 15-month prison stint. The track features on his sophomore mixtape Made in the Pyrex.

The song’s aesthetic is associated with the “crips” as the visuals and artwork both pose blue colours and bandanas – with “Woi” being a crip gang call.

Digga returns with his trademark jumpy and humorous take on UK Drill, sporting fun wordplay and pun whilst narrating his violent lifestyle and gang affiliations. This song also went viral on TikTok through the #WoiChallenge.

Digga D previewed “Toxic” on Instagram Live on February 10th, 2021, the same day he announced his sophomore mixtape Made In The Pyrex. The song serves as bonus track on the mixtape.

The song was released on the 14th of February as a Valentines Day special, and stands at the second offical single for his sophomore project. The visuals were teased with a trailer, which was later taken down within 30 minutes due to how sexually explicit it was.

The song narrates Digga’s bachelor lifestyle as it explores his sexual relations with social media influencers and how they only want him due to the fact that he’s a famous rapper. He namedrops UK social media news outlets UK Gossip TV and The Shade Borough, who frequently feature stories about Digga D due to his controversial lifestyle.

“Bluuwuu” is Ladbroke Grove, West London artist Digga D’s fifth single released from his sophomore mixtape Made in the Pyrex following “Toxic”, “Bringing It Back”, “Chingy (It’s Whatever)” and “Woi”.

Digga speaks on his gang ties and affiliations as a Crip – with the term “Bluuwuu” even being a Crip call.

Digga D teased the single originally in October 2020 on Instagram, but revisited it following receiving acclaim from his verse in the #GW20 Groundworks Cypher where he mentions meeting Nicki Minaj when he was younger, alluding to a video that went viral in 2020. He teased to drop this on the 21st of January as his new single after revealing a teaser of the tracks visuals, a day after the Cypher. He dropped the “Bad Guy” Instagram Freestyle instead and officially released the track a month later.

songs.title: P4DP

description.plain:
On P4DP, a single released in advance ‘Double Tap Diaries EP’, Digga D uses his characteristic wordplay and quick succession rhyming to assert himself as one of the most influential artists to rise out of London’s drill scene. The chorus serves as both a tribute to the artist’s history and a reminder to critics that Digga D is on top of his game.

The rise in popularity of UK Drill music, partly spearheaded by Digga D, has brought with it increasingly more elaborate music videos. P4DP, by no means an exception to this, is accompanied by visuals similar to that of CGM’s “Who?”, one which also takes place in a Gothic setting.



Wordplay, a prominent feature of Digga D songs, is ever present, with themes relating to fellow UK artists Headie One and Kojo Funds, FIFA (and football in general), Vladimir Putin and the MOBO awards – to name a few – offering means for Digga D to express his now established lyricism.

The music video also brings about a cameo for the recently released Huncho, a close friend of Digga D. Digga D’s decision to still include those who are close to him within his music videos (as seen in No Diet) as a budding solo artist speaks volumes of CGM’s close-knit community values.

Digga D continues to discover more flows and, accompanied by the talent of Suave, who is in charge of the visuals, will surely see success in P4DP.

songs.title: Red Light Green Light

description.plain:
“Red Light Green Light” is Digga D capitalising off the huge success of the viral 2021 Korean television show, Netflix’s Squid Game – in which featured the popular kids game Red Light, Green Light being played in Episode 1 with dire consequences.

The track was first previewed on Digga’s Instagram Story on the 6th of October, later announcing a TikTok challenge to give his fans a chance to appear in the upcoming music video. It was later officially announced on the 17th of October with a TikTok trailer of the Squid Game inspired music video.

This track is inspired by young British comedian Papz14, who in which uploaded a funny skit on video sharing social media TikTok of rappers “self-snitching” on a Squid Game sampled drill beat. Digga commented on the video, endorsing the idea, though the message has yet been deleted. Papz also featured on the “Red Light Green Light” music video as seen in this TikTok.
